                                    ›             ÐÌÁÔÏÔåòí              ›                                    ›› ÎÏÔÅº  This documentation  is very ›much  preliminary,  and is  subject›to change.››› ×èáô éó ÐÌÁÔÏÔåòí¿ ›››PLATOTerm  is  a terminal emulator›for your ATARI computer. It allows›you to connect your ATARI computer›to  PLATO  based on-line  services›using a serial interface, and a›suitable Internet connectivity ›device, such as an ESP8266.››PLATOTerm interprets the terminal›control commands issued from the›PLATO host, and renders a 320x192›representation of the display, while›also translating the input from not›only your keyboard, but a supported›pointing device, as touch screen›information.››› ×èáô ÷áó ÐÌÁÔÏ¿ ››PLATO was a time-sharing service ›which was operated by the University›of Illinois Urbana-Champaign from›1962 until NOVANet shut down, in›2015.››Due to the efforts of the CYBER1.ORG›organization, not only have they›been running a long-standing PLATO›server on the Internet since 2004, ›but they have also provided a dist-›ribution of a runnable PLATO system›which can be run by anyone wishing›to operate a PLATO system. As a ›consequence, two major PLATO systems›are now running on the Internet:›Cyber1.org, and IRATA.ONLINE. ››This terminal program allows you to›access these srvices, from your ›ATARI computer.››Should you want more historical›information on PLATO, you should›read Brian Dear's excellent book:›"The Friendly Orange Glow."››› Óùóôåí Òåñõéòåíåîôó ›››To run PLATOTerm, your system must›meet the following requirements:››* Atari 8-bit computer›* 48K of RAM›* a compatible R: interface›* a suitable Internet MODEM››› Óõððïòôåä Òº Äåöéãåó ›››The following R: devices have been›tested, and are known to work with›PLATOTerm:››* Atari 850›* ICD P:R: Connection›* R-Verter›* ICD Multi-I/O Interface›* CSS BlackBox Interface››Len Spencer's hyperspeed R: handlers›have been provided on-disk for both›the ICD Multi-I/O and CSS BlackBox›interfaces.››› Óõððïòôåä Éîôåòîåô ÍÏÄÅÍó ›››Since the currently extant PLATO ›services are accessible via ›Internet, you must have an Internet›MODEM, which attaches to your serial›interface, and provides a "virtual›MODEM" that talks TCP to the PLATO›host. Many devices provide this,›such as:››* cbmstuff WiModem-232›* A Raspberry Pi running TCPser››The setup of these devices is beyond›the scope of PLATOTerm, and are not›covered in this documentation.››› Ìïáäéîç ÐÌÁÔÏÔåòí ›››The binary file to load PLATOTerm is›PLATO.COM, and can be loaded either›from DOS 2.5 (which is provided on›the distribution disk), or via›SpartaDOS (including X.)››If you boot the disk, DOS 2.5 will›load the R: handler automatically.›You may choose to rename one of the›handlers to AUTORUN.SYS, to load›the handler automatically on boot.››› Æéìåó ïî ôèå äéóë ›››ATRAMI.MOU   - Amiga Mouse driver›ATRJOY.MOU   - Joustick driver›ATRST.MOU    - ST Mouse Driver›ATRTRK.MOU   - Trackball driver›ATRTT.MOU    - Touch Tablet driver›ATRRDEV.SER  - R: Driver›AUTORUN.SYS  - R: Handler ›INSTALL.COM  - Spartados Installer›MEM.SAV      - needed for PLATOTerm›PLATO.COM    - PLATOTerm Program›RHND850.COM  - R: 850 Handler›RHNDBB.COM   - R: Blackbox Handler›RHNDMIO.COM  - R: Hyperspeed MIO ›RHNDRVER.COM - R: R-Verter››› Éîóôáììéîç ôï Óðáòôáäïó Èáòä Äéóë ›››The PLATOTerm distribution disk ›contains INSTALL.COM, which can›install PLATOTerm, and its support›files to a directory on a hard›disk.››Start the installer by typing›INSTALL.››Once started, the installer will›inform you that it will attempt›to install PLATOTerm, followed by›asking you for a desired handler.››Once a handler is selected, the›installer will ask you for a›destination path. ››** The destination path should be›** specified as an absolute path in›** SpartaDOS format, e.g.:›** D1:>PLATO to install it to a new›** directory called PLATO on D1:››The installer will then copy›PLATOTerm to the destination›directory. ›› Îïôåº  Any directories which do ›not automatically exist on the ›target drive, are created ›automatically. ››› Õóéîç ÐÌÁÔÏÔåòí ›››Once PLATOTerm has been loaded, you›will be greeted with the PLATOTerm›logo, followed by the message:››PLATOTerm Ready - OPTION FOR SETUP.››This indicates that PLATOTerm is›ready for use.››When PLATOTerm starts, it starts in›TTY mode, which passes what you›type, directly to the MODEM. You›will use this mode to instuct your›MODEM to connect to your desired›PLATO host.››There currently is no "phone book"›so you will need to type commands›to your modem, to initiate the›connection, e.g.:››-----------------------------------›ATDTIRATA.ONLINE:8005›-----------------------------------›to connect to IRATA.ONLINE, or:››-----------------------------------›ATDTCYBERSERV.ORG:8005›-----------------------------------›to connect to CYBER1.ORG››› Óåôõð Íåîõ ›››PLATOTerm's configuration can be ›changed by pressing the OPTION ›key, which will present the ›following menu:››I)NTERFACE D)RIVER B)AUD T)OUCH›S)AVE E)XIT››I)NTERFACE - to select the desired›interface. Currently, only serial›interfaces are supported, but this›will have the ability to select›Ethernet, in the future, for›devices such as the Dragon Cart.››D)RIVER - To select the desired ›driver for the selected interface.›Currently, only one driver is ›available, which talks to the R:›device.››B)AUD - Used to select the desired›speed of the serial interface.›Baud rate is initially set to ›1200 bits per second.››The available baud rates are:›3)00›1)200›2)400›9)600›Q)19200›W)38400››T)OUCH - Used to select the desired›touch interface.››-----------------------------------›The available touch interfaces are:››J)OY - Atari Joysticks›A)MIGA - Amiga Mouse›S)T - ST Mouse›T)RKBALL - Trackball (e.g. CX22)›K)OALA - Touch tablet›-----------------------------------››S)AVE - Save the current setup to›the CONFIG file, which will be›loaded when PLATOTerm starts.››E)XIT - Exit SETUP, and apply the›selected changes.››› Ôèå ÐÌÁÔÏ Ëåùâïáòä ››PLATO terminals have many special›keys which must be mapped to ›equivalents on the ATARI keyboard.››The following table shows the›mappings of these keys:››PLATO         ATARI››ANS           CTRL-A›BACK          CTRL-B›COPY          CTRL-C›DATA          CTRL-D›EDIT          CTRL-E›ERASE         BACKSPACE›FONT          CTRL-F›DIVIDE SIGN   CTRL-G›HELP          CTRL-H›LAB           CTRL-L›MICRO         CTRL-M›NEXT          ENTER›SUPER         CTRL-P›SQUARE        CTRL-Q›STOP          CTRL-S›TERM          CTRL-T›MULTIPLY      CTRL-X›SUB           CTRL-Y›SHIFT-BACK    CTRL-+ (left arrow)›SHIFT-COPY    CTRL-- (up arrow)›SHIFT-DATA    CTRL-SHIFT-D›SHIFT-EDIT    CTRL-SHIFT-E›SHIFT-HELP    CTRL-SHIFT-H›SHIFT-LAB     CTRL-= (down arrow)›SHIFT-NEXT    CTRL-* (right arrow)›SHIFT-SUPER   CTRL-SHIFT-P›ACCESS        CTRL-SHIFT-Q›SHIFT-STOP    CTRL-SHIFT-S›SHIFT-SUB     CTRL-SHIFT-Y›Exit PLATO    SELECT X›Color Up      SELECT -›Color Down    SELECT =›Text Down     SELECT +›Text Up       SELECT *››› Ãïîôáãô ›››Thomas Cherryhomes›e: thom.cherryhomes@gmail.com›twitter: tschak›facebook: thomas.cherryhomes›irata: thomas cherryhomes / atari›cyber1: tschak909 / inetd›››